"ABT 1237":"about 1237","Eaton, Ches, Eng":"Eaton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Eden, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eaton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Eaton or Eton, such as Eaton Socon (Bedfordshire), Eaton (Cheshire), or Eton (Buckinghamshire), named from either Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river’ or <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","History: Nathaneal Eaton, born in Coventry, England, <i>c.</i> 1609, came to MA in 1637 and was the first head of Harvard College, in 1638–39."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Eaton was born about 1237, in Eaton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Richard Eton De Pulford and Agnes L'Engenour. He had at least 1 son with Isabel de Stockton. He died in 1349, at the age of 113."},"et":{"ABT 1237–1349":"umbes 1237–1349","1237–1349":"1237–1349","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1252–1277":"1252–1277","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1349":"1349","1239":"1239","1237":"1237","ABT 1252":"umbes 1252","1277":"1277","11 Jun 1294":"11. juuni 1294","1252":"1252","ABT 1237":"umbes 1237","Eaton, Ches, Eng":"Eaton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eden, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1237–1349":"noin 1237–1349","1237–1349":"1237–1349","1239–Female":"1239–Kuollut","1252–1277":"1252–1277","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1349":"1349","1239":"1239","1237":"1237","ABT 1252":"noin 1252","1277":"1277","11 Jun 1294":"11. kesäkuuta 1294","1252":"1252","ABT 1237":"noin 1237","Eaton, Ches, Eng":"Eaton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Eden, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1237–1349":"environ 1237–1349","1237–1349":"1237–1349","1239–Female":"1239–Décédée","1252–1277":"1252–1277","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1349":"1349","1239":"1239","1237":"1237","ABT 1252":"environ 1252","1277":"1277","11 Jun 1294":"11 juin 1294","1252":"1252","ABT 1237":"environ 1237","Eaton, Ches, Eng":"Eaton, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Eden, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robe